\section{Using the \texttt{portland} Package}

It is sometimes necessary to typeset tables in landscape orientation instead
of the normal portrait orientation. This is not easily done, but can be
accomodated using the \texttt{portland }package. The \texttt{portland }%
package will change the page margins to the landscape orientation according
to TeX commands that are added to a document. The landscape pages must then
be typeset separately and landscape page orientation selected.

This sample document contains two instances of the same table. Both tables
are typeset in the landscape orientation. This is done by first adding the 
\texttt{portland }package to the document (select \textsf{Typeset, Options
and Packages, }the \textsf{Package Options }tab, choose \textsf{Add }\
select \texttt{portland }from the list of packages and then \textsf{OK }to
close the open dialogs). Next, insert a TeX field (\textsf{Insert, Field, Tex%
}) that contains \texttt{\textbackslash landscape }where landscape
orientation is to start and add another TeX field that contsins \texttt{%
\textbackslash portrait }where the normal portrait orientation is to resume.

The table that follows is an example of using the \texttt{portland }package
commands.

