\portrait

The first table is still too wide, even for a landscape orientation page.
This can be changed by adding sizing commands that change the font sized
used by the table. LaTeX provides a number of font sizing commands. In order
from smallest to largest, the commands are: \texttt{\TEXTsymbol{\backslash}%
tiny \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}scriptsize\ \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}footnotesize 
\TEXTsymbol{\backslash}small \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}normalsize \TEXTsymbol{%
\backslash}large \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}Large \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}LARGE 
\TEXTsymbol{\backslash}huge \TEXTsymbol{\backslash}Huge.} The \texttt{%
\TEXTsymbol{\backslash}normalsize }command selects the base font size used
by the document. Since smaller sizes are wanted, one of the first four size
commands should be used. Add the size command to the [B] TeX field that is
used to start the table. In the second table the \texttt{\TEXTsymbol{%
\backslash}footnotesize }command is used, but depending on the margins you
want a smaller size command might also be used.

